​​​Like millions of people in the United States, Sudip Upadhyay was laid off in March, as the economic fallout of the coronavirus pandemic became apparent.
Now, if he doesn’t find an employer who hires him and petitions for his work visa within the next 50 days, he may also lose his legal status.
[‘Dreamers’ in health care sector help save COVID patients while in legal limbo]Upadhyay came to the United States from Mumbai, India, in 2013 to attend graduate school at Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
His most recent work authorization came from the H-1B specialty visa, granted to foreign guest workers who have at least a four-year college degree.
This visa program is commonly associated with the information technology sector, but it is also used to employ workers in health care, education, academia and marketing, among other fields.